%%R
# Min Variance Function
minvariance <- function(assets, mu = 0.005) {
      returns  <- log(tail(assets, -1) / head(assets, -1)) # Return
        Q       <- rbind(cov(returns), rep(1, ncol(assets)), colMeans(returns))
        Q       <- cbind(Q, rbind(t(tail(Q,2)), matrix(0, 2, 2)))
        b       <- c(rep(0, ncol(assets)), 1, mu)
        solve(Q,b)
}

%%R
frontier <- function(assets) {
returns <- log(tail(assets, -1) / head(assets, -1))
       Q  <- cov(returns)
       n  <- ncol(assets)
       r  <- colMeans(returns)
       Q1 <- rbind(Q, rep(1, n), r)
       Q1 <- cbind(Q1, rbind(t(tail(Q1, 2)), matrix(0, 2, 2)))
       rbase <- seq(min(r), max(r), length = 100)
       s  <- sapply(rbase, function(x) {
           y <- head(solve(Q1, c(rep(0, n), 1, x)), n)
           y %*% Q %*% y 
       })
       plot(s, rbase, xlab = 'Returns', ylab = 'Variance', main = 'Profolio Frontier')
   }

%%R
df = function(mydata) {
    print(cov(riskpremium(mydata), riskpremium(SP500)) / var(riskpremium(SP500)))
    print(fit <- lm(riskpremium(mydata) ~ riskpremium(SP500)))
    plot(riskpremium(SP500), riskpremium(mydata))
    abline(fit, col = 'red')
    fit <- lm(riskpremium(mydata) ~ -1 + riskpremium(SP500))
    print(summary(fit))
    print(summary(lm(riskpremium(mydata) ~ riskpremium(SP500))))
    par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
    plot(fit)
    }

df = function(mydata) {

Out[204]:

For each data, we are going to difference them twice. Since they are all seasonal data, we can difference the seasonality and trend by differencing them twice.

Proof: Model: X_t = (at+b)s_t + Z_t

where s_t is seasonal function (i.e. s_t = s_t-d) Z_t is white noise

First Order Difference of Lag d: diff(X_t) = X_t - X_t-d = (at+b)s_t + Z_t - [a(t-d)+b]s_t-d + Z_t-d = ads_t-d + Z_t - Z_t-d

Second Order Difference of Lag d: diff2(X_t) = ads_t-d - ads_t-2d + Z_t - 2Z_t-d - Z_t-2d = Z_t - 2Z_t-d + Z_t-2d

Forecasting¶

In [5]: 
%%R

In stead of reading the plots manually, we can used auto.arima function to decide which ARIMA model fit for our data. However, this model didn't deal with the seasonality. Therefore, we have to fit the Seasonal ARIMA to decide which model is more fit for our data.

Function for Fitting Seasonal with ARIMA(0,1,1)¶

In [3]: 
%%R
# Google
# Fitting Seasonal with ARIMA(0,1,1)
total_fit_googl = function(x){
  arima(googl, order=c(0,1,1), seasonal=list(order=x, period=52))
}
In [4]: 
%%R
# Costco
# Fitting Seasonal with ARIMA(1,1,0)
total_fit_cost = function(x){
  arima(cost, order=c(1,1,0), seasonal=list(order=x, period=52))
}
In [5]: 
%%R
# JP Morgan
# Fitting Seasonal with ARIMA(0,1,1)
total_fit_jpm = function(x){
  arima(jpm, order=c(0,1,1), seasonal=list(order=x, period=52))
}

We wrote 3 different functions for fitting the Seasonal ARIMA for these 3 different stocks. By doing so, we can pick the better model for our stocks data.

We wrote a list to store the possible seasonal order for our data. Then we used this list for fitting the Seasonal ARIMA manually. By comparing the AIGs, we can choose the best model for each stock data. However, since the average running time for each data set is around 15 minutes, and we have 27 datasets in total. Therefore, we made the comparing processes as comments, and store the AIGs in to a list as follows.
